To those who havenâ€™t played any of the Gothic games, you are missing out on a RPG treat â€“ a vast and open world where abundance of exploration filled with non-player characters (NPCs) doing their own things thus making the Gothic series a living and breathing world. Filled with quests galore, its only mishaps is the combat system and extremely high system requirements. The journey now continues with Gothic 3 that improves some of the mishaps from the previous two however added a few more. Thatâ€™s not to say to ride is game off as the world is massive, filled with some of the most gorgeous vistas I have ever seen in a long while thus making it an explorerâ€™s heaven to boot.

Because of the massive open ended world, to complete the game wholly depends upon what you do. If you are aiming just to finish of the main quest, then donâ€™t play this. This game is designed to be explored from top to bottom and from left to right. Itâ€™s a huge world with plenty of things to discover and accomplish. The unfortunate thing is that some quests tends to be repetitive (thereâ€™s so much that I can take when ask to defeat so-and-so during those arena quests) however donâ€™t let that deter you. So if you are planning to complete this game the way itâ€™s designed, it can take easily close to 100 hours. For me, at the time of this review recorded close to 120 hours and I still got a quarter of the map to discover and then revisit  the world again to finish off the main quest line.

Granted at the time of release, the game was a buggy mess. Maybe the dispute between publisher JoWood and developer Piranha Bytes have something to do with this. Piranha Bytes â€˜leftâ€™ the game with version 1.12 (still in a buggy state) however the community, yet again, saved the day. April 2012 saw the latest version 1.75. Itâ€™s a sad state of affairs though as if the game ended at version 1.12, we will never get to see the game in its fullest glory. Version 1.75 still have minor issues however, and thankfully so, we get the see the game for what it was meant to be. An ambitious game in term of size however the world, whilst beautiful to explore, it still felt not as â€˜aliveâ€™ as in Gothic 2. A definite explorerâ€™s paradise to boot though.

